  <h1 class="hidetitle">What Every Experimenter Must Know <br />About Randomization</h1>
  <h3>Terence Kelly</h3>
  <p>This column is for experimenters and the programmers and statisticians who support them. Randomized controlled experiments offer gold-standard insight into cause and effect—the knowledge that informs our most important decisions. Unfortunately, randomization in such experiments is often botched. Randomization errors silently invalidate the interpretation of experimental results, turning a fruitful quest for knowledge into a waste of time and money—or, worse, a wellspring of misinformation. Fortunately, these fatal errors are easy to spot and fix. So whether you’re a webmaster using A/B testing to increase engagement, a medical researcher evaluating vaccines, a factory manager exploring productivity improvements, or a scientist seeking the laws that govern nature or human affairs, read on.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Intervention, Control, Assignment, and Causality</h3>
  <p>Sometimes our understanding of the world relies on passive observation alone, but we learn more by coupling observation with active intervention. Astronomers can’t insert a new planet into the solar system to see what difference it will make, but most scientists, engineers, and pragmatic decision makers can perform experiments that impose changes and measure their effects. For example, a poultry farmer who wonders whether screen time will fatten turkeys can expose his flock to television and weigh the consequences.</p>
  <p>Statistical lore<sup>27</sup> reminds us, however, that exposing <i>all</i> test subjects to an intervention veils its effects:</p> 
  <div style="margin-left:24pt;">
   <p>After a proud surgeon delivered a lecture on a procedure he’d performed many times, a medical student asked whether half of eligible patients had been set aside as a baseline for comparison. “Of course not!” thundered the surgeon. “That would have doomed half of the patients to death!” Stunned silence filled the lecture hall, and the student softly asked, “Which half?”</p>
  </div> 
  <p>So our farmer should compare a <i>treatment group</i> of turkeys that watches TV with a <i>control group</i> that doesn’t.</p> 
  <div style="float:right;width:20%;max-width:400;padding:0px 0px 10px 10px;margin:0px 0px 10px 10px;"> 
   <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3778029/assets/html/3778029_fig01.jpg" /> 
   <p><a href="https://xkcd.com/2576/" style="font-size:0.7em;"><nobr>https://xkcd.com/2576/</nobr></a></p> 
  </div> 
  <p>How should birds be assigned to these groups? If they choose for themselves in free-range fashion, misleading correlations may confound the results. For example, if gluttonous turkeys also happen to crave TV, we would end up crediting screen time for weight gain that would have happened without it. Similar correlations can arise if the farmer partitions the flock. If he unconsciously assigns friendly turkeys to treatment and surly ones to control, and if friendly birds happen to have bigger appetites, we would reach the same false conclusion as with free-range assignment. The right approach is to randomly assign test subjects to treatment and control groups, which makes biased assignment and confounding correlations unlikely.</p>
  <p>Apart from eliminating bias, random assignment serves another crucial yet underappreciated purpose: Correct random assignment confers validity upon statistical tests that draw conclusions from experimental results,<sup>7</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>12</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>20</sup> specifically <i>significance tests</i> of the <i>null hypothesis</i> that the treatment had no effect. Significance tests are meaningful and valid if <b>AND ONLY IF</b> assignment was properly randomized.</p>
  <p>Correct methodology brings enormous rewards. Randomized controlled experiments are universally recognized as the gold standard for proving cause and effect.<sup>26</sup> That’s why top medical journals permit claims of causality only when supported by randomized controlled trials<sup>10</sup> and require that randomization be documented meticulously.<sup>14</sup></p> 
  <div style="float:right;width:30%;max-width:400;padding:20px;margin:0px 0px 20px 20px;background-color:#dddddd;">
    “The simple precaution of randomisation will suffice to guarantee the validity of the test of significance, by which the result of the experiment is to be judged.” 
   <br /> – <i>R.A. Fisher</i><sup>6</sup> 
  </div> 
  <style>
.equation mi {
font-style:italic;
}
</style> 
  <p>Bogus methodology invites disaster. Botched randomization can overturn the verdicts of significance tests, which then slander effective treatments and tout worthless ones, downplay real dangers and frighten us with bugbears. Unfortunately, randomization errors are widespread in practice. Busy experimenters will be glad to learn, however, that these errors are easy to spot and that right ways are <i>easier</i> than wrong. In particular, ditching pseudo-random number generators avoids fatal pitfalls while streamlining methodology.</p>
  <p>We’ll begin by reviewing the fundamental requirements of random assignment in relation to significance tests. For clarity and brevity, we’ll illustrate general principles in the context of a very simple experimental design, but the same principles apply to more sophisticated designs.<sup>12</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>16</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>17</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>20</sup> Then we’ll consider widespread bad practices and see precisely why they negate the validity of crucial statistical tests. We’ll learn how to obtain randomness for random assignment and how to persuade colleagues mired in bad habits to change their ways. Example code simplifies several chores surrounding random assignment.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Randomization and Significance</h3>
  <p>Our poultry farmer can randomly assign <i>N</i> test turkeys to treatment and control groups in one of several ways. <i>Unrestricted</i> randomization flips a fair coin to assign each turkey, which guarantees completely unbiased assignment but might yield unbalanced groups. <i>Urn</i> randomization guarantees balanced assignment with a slightly elevated risk of confounding correlations:<sup>22</sup> The farmer places <i>N/</i>2 green and <i>N/</i>2 red jelly beans in an urn. For each turkey, he stirs the jelly beans, removes one chosen at random, notes its color, and eats it. Green assigns the turkey to TV treatment and red consigns it to control. (“Urn” is how statisticians say “bowl” when discussing randomization, or perhaps just to signal that they’re statisticians.) Both randomization procedures choose an assignment <i>equiprobably</i>, i.e., with uniform probability, from well-defined spaces of permissible assignments: Unrestricted randomization chooses from all possible assignments; urn randomization chooses from all balanced assignments.</p>
  <p>How much randomness or <i>entropy</i> is required for assignment? The basic unit of entropy is the bit. One bit of entropy is what we (hope to) obtain from a fair coin flip or some other physical source of independent and unbiased random bits. The absolute bare minimum amount of entropy required for equiprobable choice is the base-2 logarithm of the number of permissible assignments. Unrestricted randomization picks one of 2<i><sup>N</sup></i> assignments, so it requires log<sub>2</sub>(2<i><sup>N</sup></i>) = <i>N</i> bits of entropy—one bit per bird. Urn randomization chooses a balanced assignment, the number of which is given by the binomial coefficient, “<i>N</i> choose <i>N/</i>2”:</p> 
