  <p>For example, there are <i>C</i>(300, 150) ≈ 9.38 × 10<sup>88</sup> ways to urn-randomize 300 turkeys. Choosing one with uniform probability requires at least log<sub>2</sub>(<i>C</i>(300, 150)) ≈ 295.56 bits of entropy—slightly less than the 300 bits needed for unrestricted randomization, because unbalanced assignments are banned.</p>
  <p>Random assignment does not require a computer. Physical coins or urns are reasonable options sanctioned by many statisticians today, for the same reasons that casinos and lotteries continue to use dice, roulette wheels, and other mechanical contraptions: They are simple, transparent, and easy to build, maintain, and audit. If used with care, however, computers can correctly perform random assignment faster and more flexibly.</p>
  <p>Computerized random assignment should follow the simple and obvious pipeline depicted in figure 1: An unbiased random assignment algorithm feasts on an all-you-can-eat stream of true-random bits and chooses equiprobably from the space of permissible assignments. Later we’ll say more about obtaining true-random bits. For now, note that the RDSEED CPU instruction provides NIST-certified crypto-grade true-random bits at torrential rates<sup>8</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>9</sup> and is widely available on both servers and consumer-grade computers; popular compilers expose it as an intrinsic function.<sup>25</sup></p> <!--
