  <br />Figure 1. Computerized random assignment 
  <p>The random assignment algorithm in figure 1 must be tailored to the experiment design. For unrestricted randomization, the assignment algorithm uses random bits as coin flips. For urn randomization, the assignment algorithm might randomly permute a list of test subjects and then assign the top half of the shuffled list to treatment and the bottom half to control. Unbiased shuffling is a subtle art, and bad advice from seemingly authoritative sources is abundant, but correct algorithms and implementations are available.<sup>11</sup> This column’s example code includes a straightforward urn randomizer. Equiprobable assignment isn’t about arcane esoterica or obsessive-compulsive perfectionism; it’s a matter of ordinary diligence in satisfying necessary requirements.</p>
  <p>A crucial correctness criterion, <i>ex ante fairness</i>, is easy to state but elusive in the wild: There must be a moment in time, before entropy is supplied, when all permissible assignments are equally likely. If no such moment exists, the assignment procedure is not correct. Ex ante fairness is merely a restatement, in the context of random assignment, of requirements familiar in other situations. All tickets in a raffle, for example, must have the same chance of winning before the final drawing—otherwise the raffle is crooked. Later we’ll see that many assignment procedures used in practice fail this common-sense test.</p>
  <p>There is no good scientific or statistical reason to deviate from equiprobable assignment. There are several compelling reasons to get it right, but we can’t survey them all, so we’ll drill down on an important motive that methodology experts have emphasized for a century: The best statistical significance tests of experimental results demand equiprobable random assignment.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Randomization Tests</h3>
  <p>Experimental results include measurements of test subjects. Our poultry farmer, for example, records how much weight each turkey has piled on by the end of his TV experiment. The first question to ask is whether measured differences between the treatment group and the control group are due to chance alone rather than the treatment. In other words, we must test the null hypothesis that the treatment had no effect. We do this by (i) defining a function that summarizes inter-group differences as a single number; and (ii) using the function in a <i>randomization test</i>—a special significance test designed for randomized controlled experiments—to determine whether the difference between groups is so extreme that the null hypothesis is implausible. Experimental design monographs statsplain randomization tests in a dialect forbidding to the uninitiated,<sup>12</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>20</sup> but the basics are intuitive when stated in plain language.</p> 
