  <p>For (ii), a randomization test tailored to an experiment’s assignment protocol computes a <i>p-value</i>, the probability that chance alone accounts for differences between the treatment and control groups. The lower the p-value, the less plausible the null hypothesis.</p>
  <p>Randomization tests compute p-values in an intuitive way. The null hypothesis holds that the treatment had no effect, exactly as if all test subjects had arrived on day one of the experiment with their final results stamped on their foreheads.<sup>20</sup> In our notation, the null hypothesis holds that the random choice of an assignment <i>a</i> had no influence on results <i>r</i>. Difference measure <i>S</i> varies with <i>a</i> but not with <i>r</i>, because <i>r</i> is a fixed constant under the null hypothesis. By choosing an assignment equiprobably from the set of all permissible assignments, we chose the corresponding <i>S</i> value equiprobably. A randomization test therefore considers the <i>S</i> values corresponding to all permissible assignments, and computes the p-value as the fraction of these <i>S</i> values that are at least as extreme as the <i>S</i> value obtained from the experiment’s actual assignment. Formally,</p>
