  <p>Unlike many statistical tests, randomization tests do not rely on dubious or untestable assumptions; indeed, they are assumption-free.<sup>20</sup> One prominent mid-century statistician deemed them “obviously logically sound.”<sup>28</sup></p>
  <p>The p-value formula makes it clear why random assignment must be equiprobable: All permissible assignments are given equal weight in computing the p-value. If the actual assignment was generated by a biased randomization procedure with non-uniform assignment probabilities, the computed p-value is nonsense.</p>
  <p>The p-value formula also makes it clear that the <i>provenance</i> of the assignment used in the experiment matters: The p-value formula sums over the entire set of all permissible assignments, <i>A</i>. To know <i>A</i>, the randomization test must know what randomization protocol was actually used in the experiment. As we saw earlier, unrestricted randomization and urn randomization entail different sets of permissible assignments: |<i>A</i>|= 2<i><sup>N</sup></i> for the former and |<i>A</i>|=<i>C</i>(<i>N</i>,<i>N/</i>2) for the latter. Using one randomization rule for assignment and the other for the p-value computation yields a meaningless p-value.</p>
  <p>More generally, any discrepancy between the set of permissible assignments actually used for random assignment and the set used to compute the p-value, or any deviation from equiprobability in the choice of an assignment from this set, invalidates the randomization test p-value. The test will, of course, always spit out a number, but that number is meaningless if randomization was bungled. Sadly, it often is.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3><i>Anna Karenina</i> Assignment</h3> 
  <div style="float:right;width:30%;max-width:400;padding:20px;margin:0px 0px 20px 20px;background-color:#dddddd;">
    “It is possible, and indeed it is all too frequent, for an experiment to be so conducted that ... [it] cannot be said, strictly, to be capable of proving anything.” 
   <br /> – <i>R.A. Fisher</i><sup>6</sup> 
  </div> 
  <p>“All happy families are alike,” writes Tolstoy; “each unhappy family is unhappy in its own way.” Likewise with random assignment. All prudent experimenters use the moral equivalent of figure 1; each careless experimenter screws up in his own way.</p>
  <p>The most brazen malpractices employ no entropy at all. For example, assignment fails the ex ante fairness test if it employs a “random-looking” but non-random digit sequence such as π. The outcome is a foregone conclusion, completely devoid of uncertainty, no matter how random the sequence might appear. For valid significance tests, the provenance of the assignment matters. Assignment determined by a digit sequence that <i>appears</i> random won’t do; the sequence must actually <i>be</i> random. R.A. Fisher, the father of randomized controlled experiments, emphasized this fundamental fact a century ago.<sup>5</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>6</sup> Fisher and his successors would concede that non-random assignment might successfully eliminate confounding correlations. It utterly fails, however, to enable valid statistical analyses of experimental results.</p>
  <p>Lazy or misguided experimenters sometimes employ “quasirandom” assignment based on ancillary data such as test subjects’ birthdays or identification numbers. Thoughtful methodologists will have none of this. “Quasirandom resembles quasipregnant, in that they both elude definition.”<sup>22</sup></p>
  <p>The most insidious show-stopper problems arise when the true-random bit stream of figure 1 is replaced by a pseudo-random number generator (PRNG), yielding the gratuitous undersimplification depicted in figure 2.</p> <!--
