  <br />Figure 2. Pseudo-random assignment 
  <p>The problem that gets plenty of attention is “bad” PRNGs, whose output isn’t very random-looking or whose period is short. Connoisseurs of pseudo-randomness point out, correctly, that poor PRNGs have been ruining scientific endeavors for decades: “If all scientific papers whose results are in doubt because of [inferior PRNGs] were to disappear from library shelves, there would be a gap on each shelf about as big as your fist.”<sup>18</sup> For random assignment in controlled experiments, however, low-quality PRNGs are a side show that distracts attention from far more serious problems inherent in PRNG-based assignment.</p> 
  <div style="float:right;width:30%;max-width:400;padding:20px;margin:0px 0px 20px 20px;background-color:#dddddd;">
    “Whatsoever a man soweth, that shall he also reap.” 
   <br /> – <i>Galatians 6:7</i> 
  </div> 
  <p>One is that PRNGs are prone to misuse. Experimenters who don’t bother to properly seed a PRNG, for example, get a pseudo-random bit stream containing little or no randomness. A PRNG that falls back on a hard-wired default seed consumes no entropy and therefore emits none; its output is no more random than the digits of π. Popular statistical software packages and commercial randomization services seed their PRNGs with facile hacks such as process ID or time-of-day; such seeds contain too little entropy to support equiprobable assignment. Recall that unrestricted random assignment of <i>N</i> test subjects requires <i>N</i> bits of entropy and balanced assignment via urn randomization requires log<sub>2</sub>(<i>C</i>(<i>N</i>,<i>N/</i>2)) bits of entropy.</p>
  <p>Even if dutifully seeded to the hilt with true-random bits, conventional PRNGs throttle the entropy that influences assignment. The size of a PRNG seed is typically much too small for equiprobable random assignment, even for modest <i>N</i>. Earlier we saw that randomizing 300 subjects requires far more entropy than will fit through most PRNG seed interfaces. If <i>N</i> = 300, even a 256-bit seed arbitrarily precludes all but an unknown, haphazardly selected, non-random, and infinitesimally small fraction of permissible assignments. This introduces enormous bias into the assignment process and makes total nonsense of the p-value computed by a randomization test.</p>
  <p>What if <i>N</i> is so small that the number of permissible assignments, |<i>A</i>|, is smaller than the number of PRNG seeds (2<i><sup>B</sup></i> for a <i>B</i>-bit seed)? Assignment can’t be equiprobable if |<i>A</i>| does not evenly divide 2<sup>B</sup>, which doesn’t happen in practice for balanced assignment. If you’re skeptical, try to find realistic values of <i>N</i> and <i>B</i> such that <i>C</i>(<i>N</i>,<i>N/</i>2) evenly divides 2<sup>B</sup>.</p>
  <p>By far the biggest problem gets near-zero attention: PRNG-based random assignment inherently and inevitably <i>guarantees</i> that assignments are <i>not</i> chosen equiprobably. To understand why, view PRNG-based assignment as an opaque machine that maps a seed to an assignment, as shown in figure 3. Think of a PRNG seed as a ball that the machine pseudo-randomly tosses at bins representing permissible assignments. Now imagine that the machine flings every possible seed. The resulting distribution of balls into bins will be far from uniform: Some bins end up with more balls than others, and some bins end up empty—even, perhaps surprisingly, when the number of balls is considerably larger than the number of bins. Choosing a PRNG seed with uniform probability means choosing an <i>assignment</i> according to the highly non-uniform distribution of balls across bins.</p> 
