  <p>In summary, elementary counting arguments and the balls-into-bins perspective show that PRNG-based assignment inevitably creates enormous deviations from equiprobability, thereby invalidating the randomization tests that indicate whether experimental results were statistically significant. Randomized controlled experiments should always use the straightforward approach of figure 1, feeding true-random bits directly into an unbiased random assignment algorithm. <b><i>
     <underline>
      Never use a PRNG for random assignment
     </underline></i></b>.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Consider the Source</h3>
  <p>Where do we get true-random bits? The easiest entropy source is the aforementioned CPU instruction, which is likely built in to several computers that you own. RDSEED extracts entropy from thermal noise.<sup>8</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>9</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>25</sup> In seconds it can generate enough true-random bits for random assignment in the largest controlled experiments. Randomizing thousands or millions of test subjects requires a few dozen random bits per subject. Recording these random bits to facilitate repeatability is no more difficult than recording a PRNG seed and is the least of an experimenter’s bookkeeping burdens.</p>
  <p>To roll your own weak entropy source, use physical phenomena that are neither predictable nor controllable in the context of your application. Deterministic physical systems such as roulette wheels sometimes meet these criteria and are widely used for serious purposes, where money is at stake. Beware, however, that determinism can be exposed with a modicum of effort. A Stanford professor, for example, has built a machine that gives a fair-looking coin flip that always lands heads up.<sup>3</sup> So-called “chaotic” physical systems are technically deterministic but much more difficult to predict or control because they are very sensitive to minor perturbations. Content delivery network Cloudflare extracts random bits for security-sensitive purposes from the chaotic dynamics of lava lamps and double pendulums.<sup>21</sup></p>
  <p>For a strong entropy source, use a truly random physical phenomenon such as radioactive decay. The most diligent true-random number generators have long employed Geiger counters and radioactive material;<sup>19</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>29</sup> Cloudflare uses uranium.<sup>23</sup> Every academic, industrial, and governmental research organization that conducts randomized controlled experiments could easily afford to establish an “Office of Random Bits” to serve local needs. The requisite know-how and kit are commonly found in high school physics labs.</p>
  <p>As a final belt-and-suspenders precaution, combine two or more unrelated and independent true-random bit streams via bitwise XOR. If a particular bit of one of the input streams is truly random, the corresponding bit of the output stream will also be truly random.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Newton’s First Law</h3>
  <p>Serious experimental work is usually done by teams of domain experts, statisticians, and programmers. If I have convinced you that controlled experiments require proper randomization, and if randomization in your neighborhood isn’t yet proper, how do you persuade your colleagues to change?</p>
  <p>First, keep in mind that your teammates, no matter how highly educated, are as human as anyone else. They have blind spots. They’re prone to inertia and stubbornness; some cling to bad habits with the steadfast defiance of a man who smokes through his tracheotomy. And they can react badly when informed that they’ve been screwing up something important, as Semmelweis learned the hard way.<sup>24</sup></p>
  <p>One approach to selling proper randomization is to skip the awkward retrospective on past mistakes and instead emphasize the superior convenience of sound practices. Figure 1 is simpler than figure 2. Both require high-quality true-random bits, which nowadays are readily available in abundance, but only figure 1 puts those bits to good use. The approach of figure 1 is easy and, most importantly, it places a crucial aspect of your methodology beyond reproach. If you’re in charge of your team’s random-assignment software, you could even make the change unilaterally, with little fanfare—“nothing to see here, just a wee tiny software upgrade.” Nobody will ever complain. There are absolutely no scientific or statistical reasons to avoid scrupulously correct, strictly equiprobable random assignment.</p>
  <p>An alternative approach is to encourage a thoughtful conversation about methodology among all stakeholders. If your current random assignment method is not equiprobable, invite your colleagues to articulate the advantages of haphazardly selecting an assignment with non-uniform probability. Everybody knows about the disastrous consequences of biased <i>sampling</i>;<sup>30</sup> why is biased assignment any better? If your team doesn’t use randomization tests to evaluate the statistical significance of experimental results, ask for a justification from first principles of the tests that are used. Don’t be surprised to hear farfetched assumptions, otherworldly models, and weak excuses. Forcing surreal hogwash to be spoken aloud can be the first step toward reform, especially if the rationalizations offered are among those already debunked by experts. See, for example, Sections 6.2 and 6.3 of Rosenberger and Lachin<sup>20</sup> and page 1051 of Neter et al.<sup>17</sup></p>
  <p>Persuading colleagues to change their ways is a slow business, requiring patience and tact. But sound methodology is worth the effort. It determines whether experiments yield valid insights into causality, versus misinformation masquerading as science.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Drilling Deeper</h3>
  <p>Modern texts present randomization tests in greater generality<sup>20</sup> and explain them in terms of the philosophy of science.<sup>12</sup> They don’t explain how to generate all permissible assignments for urn randomization, as needed to compute p-values, but Knuth does.<sup>13</sup> Bentley surveys random sampling algorithms<sup>1</sup> and a previous Drill Bits column covers unbiased random shufflers,<sup>11</sup> both of which can be used for random assignment. Munroe uses significance tests to link green jelly beans to acne.<sup>15</sup></p>
  <p>Deliberate and statistically principled random assignment in controlled experiments is a remarkably recent invention. R.A. Fisher, working with pragmatic agronomists striving to increase the bounty of England’s harvests, spelled out the basics less than a century ago.<sup>5</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>6</sup> Fisher’s pioneering work is still worth reading, though his views on other topics have not worn well: He doubted that smoking is harmful and, like many early statisticians, got mixed up in the pseudo-scientific misanthropy of eugenics.<sup>2</sup><sup>,</sup><sup>4</sup></p>
  <h4>Bits</h4>
  <p>Grab the example code tarball at <a href="https://queue.acm.org/downloads/2025/Drill_Bits_16_example_code.tar.gz">https://queue.acm.org/downloads/2025/Drill_Bits_16_example_code.tar.gz</a>. You get an RDSEED driver, a program to merge files full of true-random bits, instructions on how to perform random assignment, answers to selected Drills, and a few other stocking stuffers.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Drills</h4>
  <p>The exercises below emphasize thinking rather than coding, but there’s plenty of useful work for programmers to do. One valuable contribution they can make is digging into the guts of random assignment software to find and fix bugs.</p>
  <p>1. Does random assignment require fresh-minted entropy, or may we use “canned” and/or “recycled” randomness (e.g., from an old-fashioned table of random numbers)? Does it matter if others have used the same random numbers for unrelated purposes?</p> 
  <div style="float:right;width:25%;max-width:250px;padding:10px;margin:10px;"> 
   <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3778029/assets/html/3778029_fig05.jpg" style="width:100%;max-width:250px" /> 
   <br /> 
  </div> 
  <p>2. Is random assignment the only situation where provenance matters? Imagine that the police have caught you in the act of printing fake currency. At trial you argue that your $20 bills aren’t counterfeit because they’re indistinguishable from bills printed by the government. Does the court care where cash comes from?</p>
  <p>3. How do the counting arguments and the balls-into-bins analysis of PRNG-based random assignment change if a cryptographically secure PRNG is used?</p>
  <p>4. Meditate on the sheer perversity of unrestricted randomization using the apparatus of figure 2.</p>
  <p>5. Modify the R statistical software platform to ingest random bits from a file. For a precedent, check out the “<code>--random-source</code>” option of the GNU <code>shuf</code> utility.</p>
  <p>6. Does non-equiprobable randomization undermine the validity of statistical significance tests other than randomization tests?</p>
  <p>7. Is it possible to construct a simple device that makes random consequences of radioactive decay visible to the naked eye?</p>
  <p>8. Study the many snafus that have plagued true-random number generators, including recent examples such as CVE-2025-62626.</p>
  <p>9. Unrestricted randomization can place all test subjects into one group. How should experimenters avoid this possibility? Must randomization tests change?</p>
  <p>10. The p-value formula of a randomization test iterates over the set of permissible assignments, <i>A</i>, which can be enormous. Parallelize the p-value computation. What’s the largest <i>N</i> you can handle with $20 of rented computer time?</p>
  <p>11. If |<i>A</i>| is so huge that even parallel computation of p-values is infeasible, must we abandon the randomization test and fall back on some other significance test? (Hint: How do statisticians handle populations too large for a full census?)</p> 
  <p>12. How many randomized controlled trials informed the 1960s conclusion that smoking causes lung cancer?</p> 
  <div style="float:right;width:25%;max-width:250px;padding:10px;margin:10px;"> 
   <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3778029/assets/html/3778029_fig06.jpg" style="width:100%;max-width:250px" /> 
   <br /> 
  </div> 
  <p>13. The turkeys in our farmer’s treatment group learned from TV of their impending holiday fate. They stormed the Capitol, demanding that Thanksgiving be abolished. Will the President pardon them?</p>
